Xorsearch-XORSearch is a specialized command-line tool designed to scan a file for a specific target string even if that string has been obfuscated using XOR, ROR (Rotate Right), ROL (Rotate Left), or Shift operations.
Command: xorsearch filename.exe http
Ex:If a malware author wants to hide the string http://malicious-domain.com, they might encrypt it with a single-byte XOR key (for example, 0x5A).
Regular strings sees only unreadable, garbled binary noise.
XORSearch brute-forces all 256 possible single-byte XOR keys in milliseconds, checking if any of them reveal the target string.

Olemeta-olemeta is a specialized, open-source command-line tool used to extract all the standard properties and metadata from OLE files—most notably legacy Microsoft Office documents (like Word .doc, Excel .xls, and PowerPoint .ppt).

oleid- oleid is for quickly assessing its threat level. It acts as a rapid scanner that analyzes Microsoft Office files (both legacy .doc/.xls and modern .docx/.xlsx) to flag structural anomalies and high-risk characteristics typically used by malware.

olevba-It is arguably the most powerful and widely used tool in the python-oletools suite. Its sole job is to extract and analyze VBA (Visual Basic for Applications) macros from Microsoft Office documents. 
It doesn't just pull the raw code out; it actively parses, decompiles, and performs static code analysis to surface hidden malicious behaviors, obfuscated strings, and C2 indicators.
Command- olevba filename.docm

ViperMonkey (often executed via the command vmonkey or vmonkey.py) 
Command: vmonkey fiename.doc
While tools like olevba read the text statically and look for suspicious strings, vmonkey is a full VBA Emulation engine written in Python
Instead of just looking at the code, it sets up a fake, 
isolated internal runtime environment and tricks the macro into executing without actually running it on your host operating system.

